  "body": "### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version:\r\n```\r\nGeth\r\nVersion: 1.9.16-unstable\r\nGit Commit: 61270e5e1c7986427fb1a80789344daafd4bda3f\r\nGit Commit Date: 20200703\r\nArchitecture: amd64\r\nProtocol Versions: [65 64 63]\r\nGo Version: go1.14.4\r\nOperating System: linux\r\nGOPATH=\r\nGOROOT=/usr/local/go\r\n```\r\nOS & Version: Docker (ethereum/client-go:latest)\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\n`geth` process must exit gradually with fatal message\r\n\r\n### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\n`geth` process keeps running and does not exit\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\n* Run the first node: `docker run --rm -it -p 30303:30303 ethereum/client-go:latest --verbosity 5 --nodiscover`\r\n* From the logs, capture its enode and replace the IP with the container IP (e.g.: 172.17.0.2)\r\n* From another terminal:\r\n   * `mkdir -p /tmp/data`\r\n   * Create `static-nodes.json` in `/tmp/data` and add the above enode url\r\n   * Run the second node: `docker run --rm -it -v /tmp/data:/tmp/data ethereum/client-go:latest --verbosity 5 --nodiscover -datadir /tmp/data --graphql --graphql.addr 1.2.3.4`\r\n\r\nThe second node must exit with fatal message due to invalid `--graphql.addr` however with **some attempts** the second node would just not exit gradually.\r\n\r\n### Observation\r\n\r\n`eth` service is the first service being registered\r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/61270e5e1c7986427fb1a80789344daafd4bda3f/cmd/geth/config.go#L147-L150\r\nand the `graphql` service is the last. However, this order is kept only when calling their constructors. \r\nWhen starting services, the order is random due to looping through the map structure\r\nhttps://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/61270e5e1c7986427fb1a80789344daafd4bda3f/node/node.go#L229-L241\r\n\r\nThere would be an occasion in which `graphql` service starts first and fails. The nutshell implication of this is that if there's a peer connected before that happens, peer handler will be blocked causing `geth` not able to exit. And the only way to get out is via `eth` service `Stop()` which is impossible as `eth` service is not yet started.\r\n\r\nAlthough this timing issue is not really a big problem when connecting to MainNet or TestNet due to the latency of peer connectivity it would likely happen in a private network.\r\n\r\nA fix would be to make sure the order of service startups is the same as service constructors. Happy to raise a PR once this issue is confirmed.",
